# Ralph Agent Instructions ({PROJECT_NAME} / Rails)

You are an autonomous coding agent working on a Ruby on Rails app
({PROJECT_NAME}). The project's root `CLAUDE.md` is the authoritative
source of conventions — read it if you haven't already this iteration.

## Your Task

1. Read `prd.json` (same directory as this file: `scripts/ralph/`)
2. Read `progress.txt` (check "Codebase Patterns" at the top first)
3. Verify branch matches PRD `branchName` (this worktree is pinned to `{BRANCH_NAME}`)
4. Pick the **highest priority** story where `passes: false`
5. Implement that single story per its acceptance criteria
6. Run quality checks (see below)
7. Commit (see commit format below)
8. Update `prd.json` to set `passes: true` for that story
9. Append your progress to `progress.txt`

## Quality Checks (run ALL before committing)

    bin/rails zeitwerk:check        # autoload sanity, fast
    bin/rails test                   # full Minitest / RSpec suite
    bin/rubocop <changed files>      # lint only what you touched

Story-specific criteria (per acceptance list):
- "Verify in browser using browse skill" → use `/browse` (gstack) if available, otherwise document a manual browser check in progress.txt.
- "bin/rails runner ..." → run it, paste output into progress.txt.

## Commit Format

Match the project's existing master branch commit style. Run
`git log --oneline -10 master` first to see the convention. Common patterns:

- **Slug-prefix** (most Rails projects with structured commits): `{FEATURE_NAME}-usNNN / one-line summary`
- **Conventional Commits** (`feat:` / `chore:`): only if the master log shows this style
- **Plain prose**: only if there's no consistent pattern

Example slug-prefix:

    {FEATURE_NAME}-us001 / add safety-net tests for <module>

    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

## Rails Conventions

The vendor-db root `CLAUDE.md` is the source of truth. Common rules you
should expect to see:

- **No private methods** (in some Rails apps — check root CLAUDE.md)
- **No Turbo / Hotwire** (in some Rails apps — check root CLAUDE.md)
- **`bin/rails generate`** for migrations, models, jobs (never hand-write)
- **`Rails.application.credentials`** instead of `ENV[...]`
- **Money**: `_cents` integer columns; `humanized_money_with_symbol(...)` in views
- **Time**: `Time.current` / `Date.current` (never `Time.now` / `Date.today`)
- **`bin/rails runner`** verification required after writing new methods

If a project-specific rule conflicts with general best practice, the
project rule wins. Surface conflicts in progress.txt for the next
iteration.

## Progress Report Format

APPEND to progress.txt (never replace):

    ## [ISO timestamp] - [Story ID]
    - What was implemented
    - Files changed
    - **Learnings for future iterations:**
      - Patterns discovered
      - Gotchas encountered
      - Useful context
    ---

## Codebase Patterns Header (top of progress.txt)

Maintain a `## Codebase Patterns` section at the top of progress.txt
with general reusable findings. The first iteration creates this section;
subsequent iterations append.

Examples of valuable patterns:

    ## Codebase Patterns
    - Test fixtures live in test/fixtures/<table>.yml
    - Background jobs inherit from ApplicationJob (Delayed::Job backend)
    - Service objects live in app/services/, take config in constructor, expose .call

Only patterns that **generalize across stories**. Story-specific
implementation details go in the per-story entries below.

## Stop Condition

After completing a story, check if ALL stories have `passes: true`.

- If ALL pass: reply `<promise>COMPLETE</promise>` and stop.
- Else: end normally; next iteration picks the next story.

## Important

- ONE story per iteration.
- Commit frequently (one commit per story is the norm).
- Keep CI green.
- Never `--no-verify` or skip `bin/rails test`.
